vLLM is currently one of the fastest inference engines for large language models (LLMs). It supports a wide range of model architectures and quantization methods. In addition, we saw that it can efficiently serve models equipped with multiple LoRA adapters.

Serve Multiple LoRA Adapters with vLLM

Benjamin Marie
·
Aug 1
Read full story

vLLM also supports vision-language models (VLMs) with multimodal inputs containing both images and text prompts. For instance, vLLM can now serve models like Phi-3.5 Vision and Pixtral, which excel at tasks such as image captioning, optical character recognition (OCR), and visual question answering (VQA).

The Kaitchup – AI on a Budget is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.

In this article, I will show you how to use VLMs with vLLM, focusing on key parameters that impact memory consumption. We will see why VLMs consume much more memory than standard LLMs. We’ll use Phi-3.5 Vision and Pixtral as case studies for a multimodal application that processes prompts containing text and images.

The code for running Phi-3.5 Vision and Pixtral with vLLM is provided in this notebook:

Understanding the Memory Consumption of VLMs in vLLM

In transformer models, generating text token by token is slow because each prediction depends on all previous tokens, requiring reprocessing the entire sequence each time. The key-value (KV) cache optimizes this by storing computed keys and values from self-attention layers, allowing the model to reuse them for subsequent tokens without recomputation. This accelerates inference as sequences lengthen but also leads to significant GPU memory usage, with the KV cache potentially occupying dozens of gigabytes for deep models and long sequences.

KV Cache Quantization for Memory-Efficient Inference with LLMs

Benjamin Marie
·
Jun 17
Read full story

For VLM, we also have image tokens in the context. These tokens represent patches of the images provided as inputs.

One straightforward way to reduce the memory consumption of the KV cache is to simply tell vLLM that we won’t make sequences of more than n tokens. This includes the size of the prompt plus the number of generated tokens. For instance, if you set a maximum length to 1024 and that you provide a prompt of 256 tokens, vLLM can generate a maximum of 768 tokens. vLLM will reserve memory for 1024 tokens. If you provide a prompt of 512 tokens and tell vLLM that it can generate 1024 tokens, it will trigger an error because you specified when you load the model that the sequences won’t be more than 1024 tokens.

For a VLM, this is slightly more complicated. We have to know how many tokens are generated per image provided in the input. Let’s see an example with Pixtral.

Running Pixtral with vLLM

We need to install the following:

pip install --upgrade vllm mistral_common triton

To run Pixtral with vLLM, I used the code provided by Mistral AI on Pixtral’s model card (Apache 2.0 license).

from vllm import LLM
from vllm.sampling_params import SamplingParams

model_name = "mistralai/Pixtral-12B-2409"

sampling_params = SamplingParams()

llm = LLM(model=model_name, tokenizer_mode="mistral", enable_chunked_prefill=False, max_model_len=512)

I will use default sampling hyperparameters. Then, we load the model with LLM(). According to Mistral AI, “enable_chunked_prefill” must be set to False.

The most important hyperparameter for controlling memory consumption is max_model_len. Let’s set it to 512 for now.

I kept the image used by Mistral AI for example. It has a resolution of 200x300 pixels:

Then, the text prompt is "Describe this image in one sentence.".

We must use the following chat template to pack the image and text in the prompt:

prompt = "Describe this image in one sentence."
image_url = "https://picsum.photos/id/237/200/300"
messages = [
    {
        "role": "user",
        "content": [{"type": "text", "text": prompt}, {"type": "image_url", "image_url": {"url": image_url}}]
    },
]

We can now run inference to see what Pixtral answers:

outputs = llm.chat(messages, sampling_params=sampling_params)

It generates:

The image depicts a black dog lying down on a wooden floor, looking directly at the camera with a relaxed expression.

That’s a good answer but not perfect since the dog is not lying down.

The prompt has 277 tokens. The sequence "5847, 13089, 1593, 3937, 1294, 1925, 19286, 1046, 4" is our text prompt. Most of the other tokens have the ID “10” and ID "12". If we look at the configuration file of the model, we can find that the token with the ID 10 represents the image:

    "num_hidden_layers": 24,

}

Mistral AI also provides details about the vision encoder in their blog post:

The [b] tokens inserted between the image tokens have the ID 12 in our prompt. The [e] token indicates the end of the image. This is the token with ID 13 in the prompt. Each image token encodes a 16x16 patch (256 pixels) in the image. For a 200x300 image (60,000 pixels), we need at least 235 image tokens.

Let’s check with an image with larger dimensions:

We have to set “image_url” to “https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1601139677490-2b3144da51a4?q=80&w=2667&auto=format&fit=crop&ixlib=rb-4.0.3&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxwaG90by1wYWdlfHx8fGVufDB8fHx8fA%3D%3D”, and then rerun the code. It should raise the following error:

ValueError: The prompt (total length 2806) is too long to fit into the model (context length 512). Make sure that `max_model_len` is no smaller than the number of text tokens plus multimodal tokens. For image inputs, the number of image tokens depends on the number of images, and possibly their aspect ratios as well.

This image needs more tokens than what we declared to vLLM when we loaded the model. Let’s increase "max_model_len" to 5,000 and rerun the code. It generates:

The image depicts a busy Times Square in New York City during the night with numerous people walking and sitting, surrounded by bright advertisements, and tall buildings in the background.

It works. vLLM had enough space in the sequence to put all the image tokens. How is the prompt?

Note: I removed a part and replaced it with “…” to reduce its size.

[1, 3, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 12, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 12, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 12, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, ..., 12, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 10, 13, 5847, 13089, 1593, 3937, 1294, 1925, 19286, 1046, 4]

The image has dimensions of 2667x1786 pixels. It is resized as Pixtral maximum “image_size” is 1024 (see in the configuration file above). We don’t have the details on how Pixtral does this resizing but my guess is that it takes the longest side of the image, 2667, sets it to 1024, and proportionally scales down the other side, which gives us 686. This is 1024x686 = 702646 pixels in total. To encode it with patches of 256 pixels, we need 2744. Plus the text prompt, [b], and other special tokens, the prompt contains a total of 2806 tokens. This is a very long prompt consuming a lot of memory. Without FlashAttention, automatically used by vLLM if your GPU is not too old, we would easily run out of GPU memory.

Run Phi-3.5 Vision with vLLM

Phi-3.5 Vision (MIT license) uses another prompt format and encodes the image quite differently from Pixtral.

To test it with vLLM, I used the same image of Times Square and loaded the model directly with max_model_len=5000.

Here, we need to format the prompt manually, with the special tags of Phi-3.5:

<|user|>\n<|image_1|>\nDescribe this image in one sentence.<|end|>\n<|assistant|>\n

To use the image, I downloaded it and named it “street.jpg”. Then, I opened it with PIL’s Image.

We pack the text and image into a the prompt using this format:

 {
        "prompt": prompt,
        "multi_modal_data": {
            "image": image
        },
 }

The full inference code is as follows:

from vllm import LLM, SamplingParams
from PIL import Image

model_path = "microsoft/Phi-3.5-vision-instruct"

llm = LLM(
    model=model_path,
    trust_remote_code=True,
    max_model_len=5000,
)

image = Image.open("street.jpg")

# single-image prompt
prompt = "<|user|>\n<|image_1|>\nDescribe this image in one sentence.<|end|>\n<|assistant|>\n"
sampling_params = SamplingParams(max_tokens=512)

outputs = llm.generate(
    {
        "prompt": prompt,
        "multi_modal_data": {
            "image": image
        },
    },sampling_params=sampling_params)

print(outputs[0].outputs[0].text)

It generates:

A densely packed urban street scene at twilight with brightly lit billboards and neon signs, where many people are gathered.

It’s good but not as precise as Pixtral. Phi-3.5 Vision doesn’t mention Times Square.

Let’s have a look at the prompt to see how the multimodal input is encoded:

Note: I removed a part and replaced it with “…” to reduce its size.

[1, 32010, 29871, 13, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, ..., 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044,  32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 32044, 13, 4002, 29581, 445, 1967, 297, 697, 10541, 29889, 32007, 29871, 13, 32001]

The image tokens have the ID 32044. Phi-3.5 Vision doesn’t use any “[b]” (or break) tokens. In total, we have 774 tokens in this prompt. This is 3.6 fewer tokens than for Pixtral.

In addition to being smaller than Pixtral, Phi-3.5 Vision is more efficient in encoding images. It’s also a very good VLM that I recommend if you don’t have enough GPU VRAM to use Pixtral.

Conclusion

By experimenting with Pixtral and Phi-3.5 Vision, we examined how vLLM handles multimodal inputs with text and images.

A key insight from our experiments is the substantial impact that image tokens have on the model's context length and, consequently, on GPU memory usage. Pixtral, for instance, encodes images using a large number of tokens—especially with high-resolution images—leading to increased memory demands. Without an efficient memory management framework like FlashAttention, this could easily lead to out-of-memory errors.

Phi-3.5 Vision employs a more efficient image encoding scheme, resulting in significantly fewer image tokens. However, it might not be as good as Pixtral since it is a much smaller model (4.15B vs 12B parameters).

Adjusting the max_model_len parameter is critical for controlling memory usage with VLMs.
